Introduction¶

The agent must use a map it is given to plan a path through the maze from the starting location $S$ to the goal location $G$. This is a planing exercise for a goal-based agent, so you do not need to implement an environment, just use the map to search for a path. Once the plan is made, the agent in a deterministic environment (i.e., the transition function is deterministic with the outcome of each state/action pair fixed and no randomness) can just follow the path and does not need to care about the percepts. This is also called an open-loop system. The execution phase is trivial and can be executed using a model-based reflex agent that ignores all percepts and just follows the plan. We do not implement it in this exercise.

Given that the agent has a complete and correct map, the environment is fully observable, discrete, deterministic, and known. Remember:

  • Fully observable means that the agent can see its state and what the available actions are. That means the percepts contain the complete current state.

Here, during planning, the agent always sees its x and y coordinates on the map and also seeks when it has reached the goal state.

  • Discrete means that we have a finite set of states. The maze has a finite set

of squares the agent can be in.

  • Deterministic means that the transition function contains no randomness. An action in a state will always produce the same result. Going south from the start state always will lead to the same square.
  • Know means that the agent knows the complete transition function. The

agent has the map and therefore knows how its position changes when it walks in a direction.

Tree search algorithm implementations that you find online typically come from data structures courses and have a different aim than AI tree search. These algorithms assume that you already have a tree in memory. We are interested in dynamically creating a search tree with the aim of finding a good/the best path from the root note to the goal state. Follow the pseudo code presented in the text book (and replicated in the slides) closely. Ideally, we would like to search only a small part of the maze, i.e., create a search tree with as few nodes as possible.

Tree structure¶

Here is an implementation of the basic node structure for the search algorithms (see Fig 3.7 on page 73). I have added a method that extracts the path from the root node to the current node. It can be used to get the path when the search is completed.

In [13]:
class Node:
    def __init__(self, pos, parent, action, cost):
        self.pos = tuple(pos)    # the state; positions are (row,col)
        self.parent = parent     # reference to parent node. None means root node.
        self.action = action     # action used in the transition function (root node has None)
        self.cost = cost         # for uniform cost this is the depth. It is also g(n) for A* search

    def __str__(self):
        return f"Node - pos = {self.pos}; action = {self.action}; cost = {self.cost}"

    def get_path_from_root(self):
        """returns nodes on the path from the root to the current node."""
        node = self
        path = [node]

        while not node.parent is None:
            node = node.parent
            path.append(node)

        path.reverse()

        return(path)

If needed, then you can add more fields to the class like the heuristic value $h(n)$ or $f(n)$.

Examples for how to create and use a tree and information on memory management can be found here.

# Your answer goes here
  • n: The state space size is the total number of possible states of the maze. For a maze with no walls this would be MxN where M is the number of rows and N is the number of columns. Otherwise, the state space would depend on the size, walls, and starting/end cells of the maze
  • d: The number of steps from the starting cell to the goal cell. The number of steps varies with the size of the maze. This can be calculated by counting the number of nodes from the start to the end node in the path
  • m: The largest distance from the starting cell to the goal cell or a dead end.
  • b: The maximum branching factor is 4 because there are four possible neighbors that can be explored from a given node, which is North, South, East, and West.

Task 2: Uninformed search: Breadth-first and depth-first [40 Points]¶

Implement these search strategies. Follow the pseudocode in the textbook/slides. You can use the tree structure shown above to extract the final path from your solution.

Read the following important notes carefully:

  • You can find maze solving implementations online that use the map to store information. While this is an effective idea for this two-dimensional navigation problem, it typically cannot be used for other search problems. Therefore, follow the textbook and do not store information in the map. Only store information in the tree created during search, and use the reached and frontier data structures where appropriate.
  • DSF behavior can be implemented using the BFS tree search algorithm and simply changing the order in which the frontier is expanded (this is equivalent to best-first search with path length as the criterion to expand the next node). However, this would be a big mistake since it combines the bad space complexity of BFS with the bad time complexity of DFS! To take advantage of the significantly smaller memory footprint of DFS, you need to implement DFS in a different way without a reached data structure (often also called visited or explored) and by releasing the memory for nodes that are not needed anymore.
  • Since the proper implementation of DFS does not use a reached data structure, redundant path checking abilities are limited to cycle checking.

You need to implement cycle checking since DSF is incomplete (produces an infinite loop) if cycles cannot be prevented. You will see in your experiments that cycle checking in open spaces is challenging.

def expand_node(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, actions, max_depth):
    for action in actions:
        # Calculate the next position
        row_offset, col_offset = actions[action]
        next_pos = (current_node.pos[0] + row_offset, current_node.pos[1] + col_offset)
        # Check if the move is within bounds and not a wall
        if 0 <= next_pos[0] < len(maze) and 0 <= next_pos[1] < len(maze[0]) and maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] != "X":
            # Create the next node
            next_node = Node(next_pos, current_node, action, current_node.cost + 1)
            # Check if the next node is the goal
            if maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] == "G":
                max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
                return next_node, True, frontier, reached, max_depth
            # If the next position is not reached
            if next_pos not in reached:
                reached.append(next_pos)
                frontier.append(next_node)
                # Update max depth
                max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)

    return None, False, frontier, reached, max_depth

def breadth_first_search(maze, start, goal):
    max_depth = 0
    max_nodes_memory = 0
    max_frontier = 0
    nodes_expanded = 0

    # Create the starting node
    starting_node = Node(start, None, None, 0)

    # Frontier initialization
    frontier = [starting_node]
    reached = [starting_node.pos]

    # Actions
    actions = {"North": (-1, 0), "South": (1, 0), "East": (0, 1), "West": (0, -1)}

    # If agent is already at goal when starting
    if maze[starting_node.pos[0]][starting_node.pos[1]] == "G":
        max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
        return starting_node.get_path_from_root(), starting_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

    # Loop until the frontier is empty
    while frontier:
        # Update the maximum number of nodes in memory
        max_nodes_memory = max(max_nodes_memory, len(frontier))
        nodes_expanded += 1

        # Pop the node from the frontier
        current_node = frontier.pop(0)

        # Expand the current node
        next_node, found_goal, frontier, reached, max_depth = expand_node(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, actions, max_depth)

        if found_goal:
            max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
            return next_node.get_path_from_root(), next_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

        # Update max frontier size
        max_frontier = max(max_frontier, len(frontier))
    # Failure
    return None, None, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

def expand_node_dfs(maze, current_node, frontier, actions, max_depth):
    for action in actions:
        # Calculate the next position
        row_offset, col_offset = actions[action]
        next_pos = (current_node.pos[0] + row_offset, current_node.pos[1] + col_offset)

        # Check if the move is within bounds and not a wall
        if 0 <= next_pos[0] < len(maze) and 0 <= next_pos[1] < len(maze[0]) and maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] != "X":
            # Check for cycle by ensuring the position is not already on the current path
            if not any(node.pos == next_pos for node in current_node.get_path_from_root()):
                if any(node.pos == next_pos for node in frontier):
                    # If the node is already in the frontier, remove the old instance
                    frontier = [node for node in frontier if node.pos != next_pos]
                # Create the next node
                next_node = Node(next_pos, current_node, action, current_node.cost + 1)
                # Check if the next node is the goal
                if maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] == "G":
                    max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
                    return next_node, True, frontier, max_depth
                # Add the next node to the frontier
                frontier.append(next_node)

                # Update max depth
                max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)

    return None, False, frontier, max_depth

def depth_first_search(maze, start, goal):
    max_depth = 0
    max_nodes_memory = 0
    max_frontier = 0
    nodes_expanded = 0

    # Create the starting node
    starting_node = Node(start, None, None, 0)

    # Frontier initialization
    frontier = [starting_node]

    # Actions
    actions = {"North": (-1, 0), "South": (1, 0), "East": (0, 1), "West": (0, -1)}

    # If agent is already at goal when starting
    if maze[starting_node.pos[0]][starting_node.pos[1]] == "G":
        max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
        return starting_node.get_path_from_root(), starting_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

    # Loop until the frontier is empty
    while frontier:
        # Update the maximum number of nodes in memory
        max_nodes_memory = max(max_nodes_memory, len(frontier))
        nodes_expanded += 1

        # Pop the node from the frontier
        current_node = frontier.pop()

        # Expand the current node
        next_node, found_goal, frontier, max_depth = expand_node_dfs(maze, current_node, frontier, actions, max_depth)
        
        if found_goal:
            max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
            return next_node.get_path_from_root(), next_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

        # Update max frontier size
        max_frontier = max(max_frontier, len(frontier))

    # Failure
    return None, None, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

How does BFS and DFS (without a reached data structure) deal with loops (cycles)?

Discussion¶

BFS handles loops by recording all the nodes that it visited in a data structure, which allows it to check if a potential node has already been visited. This is fine in small mazes, but in larger mazes, the data structure can become too memory intensive. DFS, on the other hand, does not have a data structure that it can use to check if a potential node has already been visited. Instead, it uses cycle checking to prevent loops. The downside of DFS is that it can get stuck in an infinite loop and not be able to reach its target because it can revisit the same nodes indefinitely.

Are your implementations complete and optimal? Explain why. What is the time and space complexity of each of your implementations? Especially discuss the difference in space complexity between BFS and DFS.

Discussion¶

My implementation for BFS is complete and optimal because it will return the fastest route to the goal, and since all step costs are equal. The time and space complexity of my implementation for BFS is O(b^d) where b is the branching factor (4 because there can be a potential of 4 neighbors), and d is the depth of the optimal solution.

My implementation for DFS is not optimal but it is complete. This is because while it will find the first path to the goal, that path may not be the most optimal path. The time complexity of DFS is O(b^m), where b is the branching factor, and m is the max depth (because it could take the longest path to the goal). The space complexity of DFS is O(b*m) because it does not store any records of visited nodes. It only knows the nodes of its current route.

This means that DFS is more efficient when space complexity is preferred.

Task 3: Informed search: Implement greedy best-first search and A* search [20 Points]¶

You can use the map to estimate the distance from your current position to the goal using the Manhattan distance (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxicab_geometry) as a heuristic function. Both algorithms are based on Best-First search which requires only a small change from the BFS algorithm you have already implemented (see textbook/slides).

# Your code goes here

def manhattan_distance(pos1, pos2):
    return (abs(pos1[0] - pos2[0]) + abs(pos1[1] - pos2[1]))

def expand_node_gbfs(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, goal, actions, max_depth):
    for action in actions:
        # Calculate the next position
        row_offset, col_offset = actions[action]
        next_pos = (current_node.pos[0] + row_offset, current_node.pos[1] + col_offset)
        # Check if the move is within bounds and not a wall
        if 0 <= next_pos[0] < len(maze) and 0 <= next_pos[1] < len(maze[0]) and maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] != "X":
            # Create the next node
            next_node = Node(next_pos, current_node, action, current_node.cost + 1)
            # Check if the next node is the goal
            if maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] == "G":
                max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
                return next_node, True, frontier, reached, max_depth
            # If the next position is not reached
            if next_pos not in reached:
                reached.append(next_pos)
                frontier.append((manhattan_distance(next_pos, goal), next_node))
                # Update max depth
                max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)

    return None, False, frontier, reached, max_depth

def greedy_best_first_search(maze, start, goal):
    max_depth = 0
    max_nodes_memory = 0
    max_frontier = 0
    nodes_expanded = 0

    # Create the starting node
    starting_node = Node(start, None, None, 0)

    # Frontier initialization using manhattan distance
    frontier = [(manhattan_distance(starting_node.pos, goal), starting_node)]
    reached = [starting_node.pos]

    # Actions
    actions = {"North": (-1, 0), "South": (1, 0), "East": (0, 1), "West": (0, -1)}

    # If agent is already at goal when starting
    if maze[starting_node.pos[0]][starting_node.pos[1]] == "G":
        max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
        return starting_node.get_path_from_root(), starting_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

    # Loop until the frontier is empty
    while frontier:
        # Update the maximum number of nodes in memory
        max_nodes_memory = max(max_nodes_memory, len(frontier))
        nodes_expanded += 1
     
        # Pop the node from the frontier
        frontier.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])
        _, current_node = frontier.pop(0)

        # Expand the current node
        next_node, found_goal, frontier, reached, max_depth = expand_node_gbfs(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, goal, actions, max_depth)
        
        if found_goal:
            max_depth = max(max_depth, next_node.cost)
            return next_node.get_path_from_root(), next_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

        # Update max frontier size
        max_frontier = max(max_frontier, len(frontier))

    # Failure
    return None, None, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

def expand_node_abfs(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, goal, actions, max_depth):
    for action in actions:
        # Calculate the next position
        row_offset, col_offset = actions[action]
        next_pos = (current_node.pos[0] + row_offset, current_node.pos[1] + col_offset)
        # Check if the move is within bounds and not a wall
        if 0 <= next_pos[0] < len(maze) and 0 <= next_pos[1] < len(maze[0]) and maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] != "X":
            # Calculate g(n) for the next node
            new_cost = current_node.cost + 1
            # If this is a new position or a cheaper path to this position is found
            if next_pos not in reached or new_cost < reached[next_pos]:
                reached[next_pos] = new_cost
                next_node = Node(next_pos, current_node, action, new_cost)
                # Calculate f(n) = g(n) + h(n)
                f_value = new_cost + manhattan_distance(next_pos, goal)
                # Check if the next node is the goal
                if maze[next_pos[0]][next_pos[1]] == "G":
                    max_depth = max(max_depth, new_cost)
                    return next_node, True, frontier, reached, max_depth
                # Add the next node to the frontier with its f-value
                frontier.append((f_value, next_node))
                # Update max depth
                max_depth = max(max_depth, new_cost)

    return None, False, frontier, reached, max_depth

def a_breadth_first_search(maze, start, goal):
    max_depth = 0
    max_nodes_memory = 0
    max_frontier = 0
    nodes_expanded = 0

    # Create the starting node
    starting_node = Node(start, None, None, 0)

    # Frontier initialization using manhattan distance
    frontier = [(starting_node.cost + manhattan_distance(starting_node.pos, goal), starting_node)]
    reached = {starting_node.pos: starting_node.cost}

    # Actions
    actions = {"North": (-1, 0), "South": (1, 0), "East": (0, 1), "West": (0, -1)}

    # If agent is already at goal when starting
    if maze[starting_node.pos[0]][starting_node.pos[1]] == "G":
        max_depth = max(max_depth, new_cost)
        return starting_node.get_path_from_root(), starting_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

    # Loop until the frontier is empty
    while frontier:
        # Update the maximum number of nodes in memory
        max_nodes_memory = max(max_nodes_memory, len(frontier))
        nodes_expanded += 1

        # Pop the node from the frontier
        frontier.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])
        _, current_node = frontier.pop(0)

        # Expand the current node
        next_node, found_goal, frontier, reached, max_depth = expand_node_abfs(maze, current_node, frontier, reached, goal, actions, max_depth)

        if found_goal:
            return next_node.get_path_from_root(), next_node.cost, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

        # Update max frontier size
        max_frontier = max(max_frontier, len(frontier))

    # Failure
    return None, None, max_depth, max_nodes_memory, max_frontier, nodes_expanded

Are your implementations complete and optimal? What is the time and space complexity?

Discussion¶

The time complexity of my Greedy best-first search depends on the heuristic. In the worst case scenario, the time complexity is O(b^m), and in the best case scenario, the time complexity is O(bd). Since b is 4, this means that the time complexity for worst and best case scenario are O(4^m) and O(4d) respectively, where d is the depth and m is the max depth. The space complexity is O(4^m) at worst, and O(4m) at the best, where 4 = b. The Greedy best-first search is complete since it is able to find a solution, but it is not optimal since it may not always find the optimal solution, as sometimes going to the node closest may not end up resulting in the shortest path overall.

The time complexity and space complexity of my A* search is O(b^d) where b = 4 and d is the depth. It is both complete and optimal since it will find both a solution, and the solution will be optimal.

How to deal with issues:

  • Your implementation returns unexpected results: Try to debug and fix the code. Visualizing the maze, the current path and the frontier after every step is very helpful. If the code still does not work, then mark the result with an asterisk (*) and describe the issue below the table.

  • Your implementation cannot consistently solve a specific maze and ends up in an infinite loop: Debug (likely your frontier and cycle checking for DFS are the issue). If it is a shortcoming of the algorithm/implementation, then put "N/A*" in the results table and describe why this is happening.

Present the results as using charts (see Python Code Examples/charts and tables).

Add charts¶

Charts and table are shown above

Discuss the most important lessons you have learned from implementing the different search strategies.

Add discussion¶

For me, implementing BFS was relatively straightfoward, however, implementing DFS was a bit more difficult. My first version of the DFS search would fail in mazes with lots of open room, most likely because it would keep going in circles. Thanks to a suggestion on the Canvas discussion board, I realized that I had to check stack does not contain the same state more than once, so I had to make sure that my algorithm checked the stack and remove the original node if the node already exists before adding.

Implemnting Greedy Best first search was also relatively straightfoward because I just needed to make an extra function to calculate the manhattan distance, and to use that distance to find the closest node to its current position. A* search gave me more trouble because I had to take the cost of the path into account to avoid continuing a path that was already expensive when another path exists that is more optimal.

DFS search on average tends to have a higher number of nodes expanded, higher path cost, and higher max depth compared to the other algorithms. DFS also does not find the optimal paths. What I find interesting is that BFS and A* are optimal, but A* has less nodes expanded compared to BFS most likely because A* has a heuristic function. A* and BFS both have either the exact same or very similar Path Cost and Max Depth

GBFS and A* has the same path cost and max depth about half of the time, which is most likely because GBFS goes to the closest node, which can be optimal, but can sometimes not if the path overall is not optimal. Therefore, GBFS and A* can get similar results depending on the structure of the maze.

DFS performs the worse overall, as it has the highest path cost and max depth out of all the searches. What is interesting is that it does not always have the highest nodes expanded compared to all the searches.

  • Undergraduate students can attempt this as a bonus task [max +5 bonus points].

IDS¶

Implement IDS (iterative deepening search) using your DFS implementation. Test IDS on the mazes above. You may run into some issues with mazes with open spaces. If you cannot resolve the issus, then report and discuss what causes the problems.

Multiple Goals¶

Create a few mazes with multiple goals by adding one or two more goals to the medium size maze. The agent is done when it finds one of the goals. Solve the maze with your implementations for DFS, BFS, and IDS. Run experiments to show which implementations find the optimal solution and which do not. Discuss why that is the case.

More advanced tasks to think about¶

Intersection as states¶

Instead of defining each square as a state, use only intersections as states. Now the storage requirement is reduced, but the path length between two intersections can be different. If we use total path length measured as the number of squares as path cost, how can we make sure that BFS and iterative deepening search is optimal? Change the code to do so.

Unknown Maze¶

What happens if the agent does not know the layout of the maze in advance? This means that the agent faces an unknown environment, where it does not know the transition function. How does the environment look then (PEAS description)? How would you implement a rational agent to solve the maze? What if the agent still has a GPS device to tell the distance to the goal?
